/*
accident.csv is a dataset with the details of accidents in 2015.
The CSV files include dozens of fields. for the purpose of our analysis we will only use a small portion of them.

Following is the structure of our dataframe based on csv.
The format is [X] Y: Z where X is the column number in the csv file, Y is the name, Z is a description

    [0]  State: State Number (See: FARS User's Manual, page 26)
    [1]  StCase: Case Unique Identifier (for the given year). Constructed from STATE + 4-Digit Consecutive Number
    [11] Day: Day of Crash
    [12] Month: Month of Crash
    [13] Year: Year of Crash
    [15] Hour: Hour of Crash
    [16] Minute:Minute of Crash
    [35] LightCondition. Possible values are as follows:
            1 - Daylight
            2 - Dark - Not Lightened
            3 - Dark - Lightened
            4 - Dawn
            5 - Dusk
            6 - Dark – Unknown Lighting
            7 - Other
            8 - Not Reported
            9 - Unknown
    [38] Weather. Possible values are as follows:
            0 - No Additional Atmospheric Conditions
            1 - Clear
            2 - Rain
            3 - Sleet, Hail
            4 - Snow
            5 - Fog, Smog, Smoke
            6 - Severe Crosswinds
            7 - Blowing Sand, Soil, Dirt
            8 - Other
            10 - Cloudy
            11 - Blowing Snow
            12 - Freezing Rain or Drizzle
            98 - Not Reported
            99 - Unknown
    [50] Fatals: Number of Fatalities that Occurred in the Crash
    [51] DrunkDrivers: Number of Drunk Drivers Involved in the Fatal Crash
*/

%sql
SELECT * FROM accident
LIMIT 10

%sql
select month, sum(fatals), count(stCase), sum(fatals)/count(stCase) as fatalities_to_accident_ratio
from accident
group by month
order by fatalities_to_accident_ratio desc

%sql
select day, month, year
from accident
group by day, month, year
having sum(fatals)/count(stCase) > (
select max(fatalities_to_accident_monthly_ratio) as fatalities_to_accidents_max_monthly_ratio
from 
(
    select sum(fatals)/count(stCase) as fatalities_to_accident_monthly_ratio
    from accident
    group by month
))
order by year, month, day

%sql
select (sum(case drunkDrivers when 0 then null else fatals end)/count(case drunkDrivers when 0 then null else stCase end))/(sum(case drunkDrivers when 0 then fatals else null end)/count(case drunkDrivers when 0 then stCase else null end)) fatalities_to_accidents_ratio_for_drunk_vs_non_drunk_drivers
from accident

%sql
/* Light condition is dark when 2/3/6 */

select (count(case lightCondition when 2 then 1 else null end)
        + count(case lightCondition when 3 then 1 else null end)
        + count(case lightCondition when 6 then 1 else null end))/count(*) as percentage_accidents_in_dark
from accident

/*
vehicle.csv is a dataset with the details of vehicles that were involved in accidents in 2015.
The CSV files include dozens of fields. for the purpose of our analysis we will only use a small portion of them.

Following is the structure of our dataframe based on csv.
The format is [X] Y: Z where X is the column number in the csv file, Y is the name, Z is a description

    [0]  State: State Number (See: FARS User's Manual, page 26)
    [1]  StCase: Case Unique Identifier (for the given year). Constructed from STATE + 4-Digit Consecutive Number
    [2] vehicleNumber: Consecutive number assigned to each vehicle in the case.  
    [20] VIN: Vehicle identification number (VIN) of this vehicle
    [4] numOccupants: A count of the number of occupants in this vehicle
    [15] maker: The make (manufacturer) of this vehicle
    [16] model: The model of this vehicle within a given maker
    [19] modelYear: The manufacturer's model year of this vehicle
    [49] travelSpeed: The speed the vehicle was traveling prior to the occurrence of the crash as reported by the investigating officer.
            0       - Stopped Motor Vehicle in Transport
            1-151   - Reported Speed Up to 151 mph
            997     - Speed Greater than 151 mph
            998     - Not Reported
            999     - Unknown
    [87] speedLimit: The attribute that best represents the speed limit just prior to this vehicle’s critical precrash event:
            0    -  No Statutory Limit/Non-Trafficway or Driveway Access
            5-80 -  Speed Limit (5 mph Increments)
            98   -  Not Reported
            99   -  Unknown
    [55] towed: The mode by which this vehicle left the scene of the crash.
            2 -  Towed Due to Disabling Damage
            3 -  Towed Not Due to Disabling Damage
            5 -  Not Towed
            8 -  Not Reported
            9 -  Unknown
*/

val vehicleRDD = sc.textFile("/resources/data/vehicle.csv").map(line => line.split(",", -1).map(_.trim)).filter(line => line(0) != "STATE")

case class Vehicle(
    state: Int,
    stCase: Int,
    vehicleNumber: Int,
    VIN: String,
    numOccupants: Int,
    maker: Int,
    model: Int,
    modelYear: Int,
    travelSpeed:Int,
    speedLimit: Int,
    towed: Int
  )

// clean up vehicle fields and convert them to proper formats
def getVehicle(row:Array[String]):Vehicle = {
  return Vehicle(
    row(0).toInt,
    row(1).toInt,
    row(2).toInt,
    row(20),
    row(4).toInt,
    row(15).toInt,
    row(16).toInt,
    row(19).toInt,
    row(49).toInt,
    row(87).toInt,
    row(55).toInt
  )
}

// load the data into a DataFrame used for SparkSQL
val vehicle = vehicleRDD.map(r => getVehicle(r)).toDF()
// register this data as an SQL table
vehicle.createOrReplaceTempView("vehicle")

/*
person.csv is a dataset with the details of persons that were involved in accidents in 2015.
The CSV files include dozens of fields. for the purpose of our analysis we will only use a small portion of them.

Following is the structure of our dataframe based on csv.
The format is [X] Y: Z where X is the column number in the csv file, Y is the name, Z is a description

    [0]  State: State Number (See: FARS User's Manual, page 26)
    [1]  StCase: Case Unique Identifier (for the given year). Constructed from STATE + 4-Digit Consecutive Number
    [3]  vehicleNumber: Consecutive number assigned to each vehicle in the case (starting from 1 for every case). 
    [4]  personNumber: Consecutive number assigned to each person in the vehicle (starting from 1 for every vehicle).
    [28] personType: The role of this person involved in the crash:
            1 - Driver of a Motor Vehicle In-Transport
            2 - Passenger of a Motor Vehicle In-Transport
            3 - Occupant of a Motor Vehicle Not In-Transport
            4 - Occupant of a Non-Motor Vehicle Transport Device
            5 - Pedestrian
            6 - Bicyclist
            7 - Other Cyclist
            8 - Person on Personal Conveyances (Since 2007)
            9 - Unknown Occupant Type in a Motor Vehicle In-Transport
            10- Persons In/On Buildings (Since 2007)
            19- Unknown Type of Non-Motorist
    [26] age: Age
            0       - Less than One Year
            1-120   - Age of the Individual in Years
            998     - Not Reported
            999     - Unknown
    [27] sex: Sex
    [52] DOA: Describes if this person died at the scene of the crash or en route to a hospital/medical facility
            0 - Not Applicable
            7 - Died at Scene
            8 - Died En Route
            9 - Unknown
*/

val personRDD = sc.textFile("/resources/data/person.csv").map(line => line.split(",", -1).map(_.trim)).filter(line => line(0) != "STATE")

case class Person(
    state: Int,
    stCase: Int,
    vehicleNumber: Int,
    personNumber: Int,
    personType: Int,
    age: Int,
    sex: Int,
    DOA: Int
  )

def getPerson(row:Array[String]):Person = {
  return Person(
    row(0).toInt,
    row(1).toInt,
    row(3).toInt,
    row(4).toInt,
    row(28).toInt,
    row(26).toInt,
    row(27).toInt,
    row(52).toInt
  )
}


val person = personRDD.map(r => getPerson(r)).toDF()
person.createOrReplaceTempView("person")

%sql
select (
    select count(*)
    from vehicle_filtered
    where travelSpeed > 0 and travelSpeed < 998
        and speedLimit > 4 and speedLimit < 81
        and travelSpeed > speedLimit
        ) / count(*) as percentage_of_vehicles_over_speed_limit
from vehicle_filtered
where travelSpeed > 0 and travelSpeed < 998
    and speedLimit > 4 and speedLimit < 81

/*

Question 2.2: 
    - Calculate the same ratio (percent of vehicles for which the travelSpeed is above the speed limit) *per maker*. 
    - Make sure you only consider makers that have more than 100 cars involved in accidents.
    - Make sure you ignore values that are not valid speed values.
    - Order the results based on the ratio (higher first)

*/

%sql
select v1.maker, v1.overLimit/v2.all as overLimitRatioPerMaker
from (select maker, count(*) as overLimit
from vehicle_filtered
where travelSpeed > 0 and travelSpeed < 998
    and speedLimit > 4 and speedLimit < 81
    and travelSpeed > speedLimit
group by maker
having maker in ( select maker from vehicle_filtered group by maker having count(1) > 100 )) v1 inner join
( select maker, count(*) as all
from vehicle_filtered
where
travelSpeed > 0 and travelSpeed < 998
    and speedLimit > 4 and speedLimit < 81
group by maker
having maker in ( select maker from vehicle_filtered group by maker having count(1) > 100 )) v2
on v1.maker = v2.maker
order by overLimitRatioPerMaker

%sql
SELECT *
FROM ( SELECT 
         personType,
         age,
         row_number() OVER (PARTITION BY personType ORDER BY age desc) AS rank
      FROM
         person
      WHERE 
         age < 121
     ) tmp
WHERE 
  rank <= 5
order by personType, rank

%sql
select drunkDrivers, avg(age)
from accident, person
where accident.stCase = person.stCase
    and age < 121
group by drunkDrivers
order by drunkDrivers

/*

Question 3.1: show the distribution of ages involved in accidents, based on age groups of 10 years (i.e., how many people of age 0-9, 10-19, etc.)
    - In order to get the age group from an age we can use the integer part of age/10. e.g. Integer(27/10) = 2.
    - You can use CAST(age/10 as INT) to get the age group
    - Make sure you ignore invalid values.
    - Order the results based on the age groups

*/

%sql
select cast(age/10 as int) as ageGroup, count(*) from person
where age < 121
group by cast(age/10 as int)
order by cast(age/10 as int)

/*

Question 3.2: 
    - Examine the distribution of ages involved in accidents, based on age groups of 10 years, *for each one of the following personTypes*:
        1. Drivers
        2. Passengers
        3. Pedestrian
        4. Bicyclist
    - Which are the two most different distributions? (provide answer in a new cell as a code comment)
*/

%sql
select cast(age/10 as int) as ageGroup, personType, count(stCase) from person
where age < 121 and (personType = 1 or personType = 2 or personType = 5 or personType = 6)
group by cast(age/10 as int), personType
order by cast(age/10 as int)

%sql
select minAge, avg(fatals) as avgFatals, (avg(fatals)-1) as avgFatalsOverOne
from
(
    select accident.stCase, fatals, min(cast(age/10 as int)) as minAge
    from accident, person
    where accident.stCase = person.stCase and age < 121
        and personType = 1
    group by accident.stCase, fatals
)
group by minAge
order by minAge

%sql
select oldestCar, avg(fatals) as avgFatals, (avg(fatals)-1) as avgFatalsOverOne
from
(
    select accident.stCase, fatals, max(cast(modelYear/10 as int)) as oldestCar
    from accident, vehicle_filtered
    where accident.stCase = vehicle_filtered.stCase
    and ModelYear < 9998
    group by accident.stCase, fatals
)
group by oldestCar
order by oldestCar

The avg fatalities per age group decreases as the age group increases. It has a linear trend with the max avg fatalities occuring to people in the 0-9 age group.

There is a peak in accidents involving cars in model year group of 1930s. The average fatalities increase after 1960 as the model year increases. This coud be because there are more cars on the road that are post 1990. The 1930 ones could be outlier cases because there aren't a lot of 1930 vehicles on the road

The age group is more interesting because there is a clear (linear) trend present in the results
